{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The transparency around open-source innovation creates unique opportunity structures that are often missing in proprietary development environments.",
    "Any contributor can directly observe, understand and build upon works of others, without the need to be in the team (Lakhani and Von Hippel 2004).",
    "Another distinctive characteristic of open-source innovation is its occurrence through a sequential layering of individual tasks rather than concurrent development facilitated by modular architecture (Medappa and Srivastava 2019).",
    "Such an approach creates an innovation environment that fosters a healthy mix of two key innovation types: building new capabilities and enhancing existing quality.",
    "Most contributions in opensource can be placed in a continuum between radical innovation that creates entirely new capabilities to incremental innovation, which enhances existing quality (Dahlander and Magnusson 2008), supporting the notion that even improvements to effectiveness and usability constitute meaningful innovation."
  ],
